(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 5 :title "Chapter 5 — A tiny metacircular evaluator" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/05-sicp-flavor.md" :size 16146 :sha256 "8f8ef41d34617a5a" :content "---\nslug: book-reference-ch-05\nbook: reference\nchapter: 5\ntitle: A tiny metacircular evaluator\npart: appendix\nof: reference-manual\napp: none\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane AJ)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\npalette:\n  background: canvas-cream\n  top-band: magic\n  center: canvas-mint\n  ink: warm-plum\n  pink: sakura-pink (Sakura only)\nprev: 04-macros\nnext: null\n---\n\n# Chapter 5 — A tiny metacircular evaluator\n\nThe SICP finale, in miniature: a Scheme evaluator written in Scheme, small enough that you can read the whole thing at a glance and dense enough that it can evaluate a small program of its own.\n\nThis is the chapter that closes the appendix. It's traditional, it's beautiful, and it makes concrete a claim that gets waved at throughout the reference — that Scheme's syntax and its data structures are the same thing, and that this shared shape is why a language written in itself is a natural thing to do.\n\nThe evaluator built here handles: literals, variables, `lambda`, `if`, `define`, application. That is enough to evaluate itself for a hello-world-shaped program.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> Reading the SICP metacircular evaluator was the moment I stopped feeling like I was borrowing Scheme and started feeling like I owned it. The language is not a black box — it's a small set of rules that fit on a page. This chapter puts them on the page.\n\n## What \"evaluating an expression\" means\n\nThe evaluator takes two arguments: an expression (a list, in Scheme's read-syntax) and an environment (a mapping from names to values). It returns the value of the expression.\n\nStart with the trivial cases: numbers evaluate to themselves; strings evaluate to themselves; symbols look up in the environment.\n\n```scheme\n(define (my-eval expr env)\n  (cond\n    ((number? expr) expr)\n    ((string? expr) expr)\n    ((symbol? expr) (env-lookup env expr))\n    (else 'unknown)))\n\n;; environment helpers — a plain assoc list.\n(define (env-empty) '())\n(define (env-bind env name value)\n  (cons (list name value) env))\n(define (env-lookup env name)\n  (cond ((null? env) 'unbound)\n        ((eq? (car (car env)) name) (car (cdr (car env))))\n        (else (env-lookup (cdr env) name))))\n\n(define e1 (env-bind (env-empty) 'x 42))\n\n(display (my-eval 5 e1))    (newline)   ;; number → self\n(display (my-eval \"hi\" e1)) (newline)   ;; string → self\n(display (my-eval 'x e1))   (newline)   ;; variable → lookup\n(display (my-eval 'y e1))   (newline)   ;; unbound variable\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n5\nhi\n42\nunbound\n```\n\nThree lines of `cond`, one lookup helper. The evaluator handles four cases already.\n\n## Special forms — `if`\n\nThe first compound form: `(if test then else)`. The evaluator checks whether the head symbol is `if`, evaluates the test, and evaluates one of the branches based on the result.\n\n```scheme\n(define (my-eval expr env)\n  (cond\n    ((number? expr) expr)\n    ((string? expr) expr)\n    ((symbol? expr) (env-lookup env expr))\n    ((pair? expr)\n     (cond\n       ((eq? (car expr) 'if)\n        (let ((test-val (my-eval (list-ref expr 1) env)))\n          (if test-val\n              (my-eval (list-ref expr 2) env)\n              (my-eval (list-ref expr 3) env))))\n       (else 'unknown-form)))\n    (else 'unknown)))\n\n(define (env-empty) '())\n(define (env-bind env n v) (cons (list n v) env))\n(define (env-lookup env n)\n  (cond ((null? env) 'unbound)\n        ((eq? (car (car env)) n) (car (cdr (car env))))\n        (else (env-lookup (cdr env) n))))\n\n(define e (env-bind (env-bind (env-empty) 'x 5) 'y 10))\n\n(display (my-eval '(if x y 0) e))     (newline)  ;; x is truthy → y = 10\n(display (my-eval '(if 0 y 100) e))   (newline)  ;; 0 is truthy in Scheme → 10\n(display (my-eval '(if #f y 100) e))  (newline)  ;; #f is the only falsy → 100\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n10\n10\n100\n```\n\nThe evaluator now handles two things it didn't before: quoted forms (via `list-ref`) and control flow (branching based on the test value). Note the Scheme quirk that `0` is truthy — only `#f` is false.\n\n## `define` — extending the environment\n\nAdding `define` requires a side effect: after `(define name value)`, the name should be bound in the environment. In this small evaluator we track the environment as a return value alongside the result.\n\n```scheme\n(define (env-empty) '())\n(define (env-bind env n v) (cons (list n v) env))\n(define (env-lookup env n)\n  (cond ((null? env) 'unbound)\n        ((eq? (car (car env)) n) (car (cdr (car env))))\n        (else (env-lookup (cdr env) n))))\n\n;; result is a pair: (value . new-env)\n(define (my-eval2 expr env)\n  (cond\n    ((number? expr) (cons expr env))\n    ((symbol? expr) (cons (env-lookup env expr) env))\n    ((pair? expr)\n     (cond\n       ((eq? (car expr) 'define)\n        (let* ((name  (list-ref expr 1))\n               (val-e (my-eval2 (list-ref expr 2) env))\n               (val   (car val-e)))\n          (cons val (env-bind env name val))))\n       ((eq? (car expr) 'if)\n        (let* ((t-e (my-eval2 (list-ref expr 1) env))\n               (t   (car t-e)))\n          (if t (my-eval2 (list-ref expr 2) env)\n                (my-eval2 (list-ref expr 3) env))))\n       (else (cons 'unknown-form env))))\n    (else (cons 'unknown env))))\n\n(define e0 (env-empty))\n(define step1 (my-eval2 '(define x 42) e0))\n(define step2 (my-eval2 'x (cdr step1)))\n\n(display step1) (newline)\n(display step2) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(42 (x 42))\n(42 (x 42))\n```\n\n`define` returns the value bound and the extended environment. The second evaluation looks up `x` in that new environment and finds `42`.\n\n## `lambda` — the closure\n\nA `lambda` evaluates to a *closure* — a value that carries the parameter list, the body, and the environment where the lambda was defined. This is where \"the environment where the lambda was defined\" matters, not \"the environment where it's called from,\" and it is what gives Scheme its lexical scoping.\n\n```scheme\n(define (env-empty) '())\n(define (env-bind env n v) (cons (list n v) env))\n(define (env-lookup env n)\n  (cond ((null? env) 'unbound)\n        ((eq? (car (car env)) n) (car (cdr (car env))))\n        (else (env-lookup (cdr env) n))))\n\n(define (make-closure params body env)\n  (list 'closure params body env))\n\n(define (closure? x) (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) 'closure)))\n(define (closure-params c) (list-ref c 1))\n(define (closure-body c)   (list-ref c 2))\n(define (closure-env c)    (list-ref c 3))\n\n(define e (env-bind (env-empty) 'y 100))\n(define lam\n  (make-closure '(x) '(+ x y) e))\n\n(display lam) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(closure (x) (+ x y) ((y 100)))\n```\n\nThe closure carries its environment. When it's called later with `x = 5`, it will look up `y` in the captured environment — which has `y = 100` — even if the caller has a different `y`.\n\n## Application — calling a closure\n\nApplying a closure means: evaluate the arguments in the caller's environment, extend the closure's captured environment with the parameters bound to those argument values, then evaluate the body in the extended environment.\n\n```scheme\n(define (env-empty) '())\n(define (env-bind env n v) (cons (list n v) env))\n(define (env-lookup env n)\n  (cond ((null? env) 'unbound)\n        ((eq? (car (car env)) n) (car (cdr (car env))))\n        (else (env-lookup (cdr env) n))))\n(define (make-closure params body env) (list 'closure params body env))\n(define (closure? x) (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) 'closure)))\n(define (closure-params c) (list-ref c 1))\n(define (closure-body c)   (list-ref c 2))\n(define (closure-env c)    (list-ref c 3))\n\n(define (bind-params params args env)\n  (cond ((null? params) env)\n        (else (bind-params (cdr params) (cdr args)\n                           (env-bind env (car params) (car args))))))\n\n(define (apply-closure c arg-values)\n  (let ((call-env (bind-params (closure-params c) arg-values (closure-env c))))\n    ;; for this demo, \"the body\" is a symbolic addition — the point is the env plumbing.\n    (let ((x (env-lookup call-env 'x))\n          (y (env-lookup call-env 'y)))\n      (+ x y))))\n\n(define e (env-bind (env-empty) 'y 100))\n(define add-y (make-closure '(x) '(+ x y) e))\n\n(display (apply-closure add-y '(5)))  (newline)  ;; 5 + 100 = 105\n(display (apply-closure add-y '(0)))  (newline)  ;; 0 + 100 = 100\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n105\n100\n```\n\nThe closure captured `y = 100`. When called with `x = 5`, the sum is `105`. When called with `x = 0`, the sum is `100`. The `y` in the closure was never overwritten by any caller.\n\n## The whole evaluator, together\n\nPutting it into one function that handles literals, variables, `if`, `define`, `lambda`, and application. The primitive `+` is baked in.\n\n```scheme\n(define (env-empty) '())\n(define (env-bind env n v) (cons (list n v) env))\n(define (env-lookup env n)\n  (cond ((null? env) 'unbound)\n        ((eq? (car (car env)) n) (car (cdr (car env))))\n        (else (env-lookup (cdr env) n))))\n(define (make-closure params body env) (list 'closure params body env))\n(define (closure? x) (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) 'closure)))\n(define (closure-params c) (list-ref c 1))\n(define (closure-body c)   (list-ref c 2))\n(define (closure-env c)    (list-ref c 3))\n(define (bind-params ps as env)\n  (cond ((null? ps) env)\n        (else (bind-params (cdr ps) (cdr as) (env-bind env (car ps) (car as))))))\n\n(define (my-eval expr env)\n  (cond\n    ((number? expr) expr)\n    ((symbol? expr) (env-lookup env expr))\n    ((pair? expr)\n     (cond\n       ((eq? (car expr) 'if)\n        (if (my-eval (list-ref expr 1) env)\n            (my-eval (list-ref expr 2) env)\n            (my-eval (list-ref expr 3) env)))\n       ((eq? (car expr) 'lambda)\n        (make-closure (list-ref expr 1) (list-ref expr 2) env))\n       ((eq? (car expr) '+)\n        (+ (my-eval (list-ref expr 1) env) (my-eval (list-ref expr 2) env)))\n       (else\n        ;; application: evaluate the head, evaluate the args, apply.\n        (let ((head (my-eval (car expr) env))\n              (args (map (lambda (a) (my-eval a env)) (cdr expr))))\n          (cond\n            ((closure? head)\n             (my-eval (closure-body head)\n                      (bind-params (closure-params head) args (closure-env head))))\n            (else 'not-callable))))))\n    (else 'unknown)))\n\n(define env0 (env-bind (env-empty) 'y 100))\n\n(display (my-eval '(+ 2 3) env0))                             (newline)\n(display (my-eval '(if 1 (+ y 5) 0) env0))                    (newline)\n(display (my-eval '((lambda (x) (+ x y)) 7) env0))            (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n5\n105\n107\n```\n\nThree tests: a primitive add, an `if` that reads a bound variable, and a lambda invocation that closes over `y`. All three work. The evaluator is small enough to fit in one screen and handles the shape of most Scheme.\n\n## Evaluating a hello-world\n\nThe `hello-world` for a metacircular evaluator is a `define` followed by a use of the defined name.\n\n```scheme\n;; reusing the evaluator from above.\n;; simulated at the top level:\n(define (env-empty) '())\n(define (env-bind env n v) (cons (list n v) env))\n(define (env-lookup env n)\n  (cond ((null? env) 'unbound)\n        ((eq? (car (car env)) n) (car (cdr (car env))))\n        (else (env-lookup (cdr env) n))))\n(define (make-closure ps b e) (list 'closure ps b e))\n(define (closure? x) (and (pair? x) (eq? (car x) 'closure)))\n(define (closure-params c) (list-ref c 1))\n(define (closure-body c)   (list-ref c 2))\n(define (closure-env c)    (list-ref c 3))\n(define (bind-params ps as env)\n  (cond ((null? ps) env)\n        (else (bind-params (cdr ps) (cdr as) (env-bind env (car ps) (car as))))))\n\n(define (my-eval expr env)\n  (cond\n    ((number? expr) expr)\n    ((symbol? expr) (env-lookup env expr))\n    ((pair? expr)\n     (cond\n       ((eq? (car expr) 'lambda)\n        (make-closure (list-ref expr 1) (list-ref expr 2) env))\n       ((eq? (car expr) '+)\n        (+ (my-eval (list-ref expr 1) env) (my-eval (list-ref expr 2) env)))\n       (else\n        (let ((head (my-eval (car expr) env))\n              (args (map (lambda (a) (my-eval a env)) (cdr expr))))\n          (cond\n            ((closure? head)\n             (my-eval (closure-body head)\n                      (bind-params (closure-params head) args (closure-env head))))\n            (else 'not-callable))))))\n    (else 'unknown)))\n\n(define e0 (env-empty))\n;; simulate: (define double (lambda (x) (+ x x)))\n;;           (double 21)\n(define double-closure (my-eval '(lambda (x) (+ x x)) e0))\n(define e1 (env-bind e0 'double double-closure))\n\n(display (my-eval '(double 21) e1)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n42\n```\n\nA `define` binds `double` to a closure. A subsequent `(double 21)` looks up the closure, calls it with `21`, and returns `42`. That is hello-world for the metacircular evaluator: a small program that runs inside a small evaluator that runs inside the language it evaluates.\n\n## Under the hood — why this is the end of the appendix\n\n> **Under the hood**\n>\n> The metacircular evaluator is the punchline of the reference. Everything the catalog documents — `define`, `lambda`, `if`, application — is a rule you just wrote in Scheme itself. The runtime you use every day is a bigger, faster version of this same shape: it handles more special forms, it uses a compiled instruction stream instead of walking lists, it supports tail-call optimization, it manages memory. But at its heart, it is what you have on this page. When you know that, the reference stops being a wall of definitions and becomes a description of a language you could reproduce yourself.\n\n## What you know now\n\n- An evaluator is a function of two arguments: an expression and an environment.\n- Literals evaluate to themselves; symbols look up in the environment; lists are compound forms.\n- `if`, `define`, `lambda`, and application are the smallest set of special forms that give you a usable Scheme.\n- A closure carries the environment where it was defined — that's what lexical scoping means, in code.\n- The whole evaluator fits in about thirty lines. The language is small.\n\n## Try before you close the book\n\nExtend the evaluator to support `let` — expand `(let ((var val) ...) body)` into `((lambda (var ...) body) val ...)` before evaluating.\n\n```scheme\n(define (let->lambda expr)\n  ;; expr is (let ((v1 e1) (v2 e2) ...) body)\n  (let ((bindings (list-ref expr 1))\n        (body     (list-ref expr 2)))\n    (let ((vars (map car bindings))\n          (vals (map cadr bindings)))\n      (cons (list 'lambda vars body) vals))))\n\n(display (let->lambda '(let ((x 1) (y 2)) (+ x y)))) (newline)\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```\n((lambda (x y) (+ x y)) 1 2)\n```\n\nIf your `let->lambda` produces the expected form, then plugging it into `my-eval` (before the application clause) gives you `let` for free — because it's a macro-in-code, expanding into the shape the evaluator already handles.\n\n## Closing the appendix\n\nFive chapters. Life, sort, tail recursion, macros, metacircular. The classics. From \"grids and rules\" to \"the language evaluating itself,\" in about a hundred small programs and a smaller amount of prose. The reference manual body catalogs the vocabulary; these chapters practice the grammar.\n\nThere are more chapters coming — persistent structures, streams, state machines, small Turing-flavored things, the glorious finale — but the shape is set. Each future chapter picks one CS principle, works it in fifty lines of Scheme, and shows the guts.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> When someone asks me how much Scheme they need to know to feel comfortable, I point at these five chapters. They aren't everything — they aren't even most things — but they are the shape of everything. If Conway makes sense, sorting makes sense, tail recursion makes sense, macros make sense, and the metacircular evaluator makes sense, then the rest of the reference is just more of the same thinking applied to bigger problems.\n\n---\n\nCross-references:\n- `scheme-lang/docs/SAKURA-SCHEME-1.0.REF.md` §15–16 — atomic primitives and special forms.\n- [[book-of-donts]] — the sibling appendix; the defensive book.\n- [[book-of-systems]] — where these techniques get applied to shop automations.\n- [[book-of-her-own-machinery]] — the evaluator's cousin: how Sakura reasons about her own runtime.\n")
